		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2008"></a><br><code>sle2008/paper08</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2008</a> paper:</span><br><i>Engineering a DSL for Software Traceability</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/NikolaosDrivalos.html">Nikolaos Drivalos</a>, <a href="../profile/DimitriosSKolovos.html">Dimitrios S. Kolovos</a>, <a href="../profile/RichardFPaige.html">Richard F. Paige</a>, <a href="../profile/KiranFernandes.html">Kiran Fernandes</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_10">10.1007/978-3-642-00434-6_10</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5g.html"><span class="tagM">T5G: Traceability</span></a><ul><li> The paper’s primary contribution is a language dedicated to defining and managing software traceability links.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> TML is a domain-specific language tailored to the domain of traceability metamodel construction.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Because TML is a metamodelling language (a language for defining traceability metamodels), it fits meta-language concerns.
</li></ul></li></ul>
